+### 8.10 Node-disruption + duplicate-Pod semantics
+
+Two distinct Kubernetes-side hazards bear on the chunk's
+correctness story:
+
+**Node disruption (eviction, drain, preemption).** With
+`backoffLimit: 0` (Decision 1), the Job controller does NOT
+reschedule a disrupted Pod; it transitions the Job to
+`status.failed: 1` with a `DisruptionTarget` Pod condition.
+The host's Job watch detects `failed > 0` (the ¬ß3.4 step 6
+"Job failed" arm) and runs the existing chapter 3 ¬ß3.3
+transport-failure mapping ‚Üí `VariantSubmission(status="error")`.
+The variant terminalizes as `error`; the next ideation cycle
+MAY produce a successor idea/variant pair that re-attempts.
+This is the same end-state as a `*_command` exit-nonzero or a
+malformed outcome.json ‚Äî there is no "node-loss" special case
+in the host's submit logic.
+
+A future amendment MAY use `podFailurePolicy` (GA in k8s
+1.31; feature-gated in 1.27-1.30) to *ignore* `DisruptionTarget`
+conditions, allowing the controller to re-create the Pod once
+on infra-shaped failures. The chart targets k8s 1.27+ per 13a
+¬ß7.5, so making `podFailurePolicy` load-bearing would force a
+1.31+ floor. 13b stays at the lower-common-denominator and
+treats every Job-failure as host-visible, accepting
+"variant-error ‚Üí re-ideate" as the recovery path.
+
+**Duplicate Pod execution.** The Kubernetes Job documentation
+warns that `completions: 1` Jobs may *very rarely* run the
+user program twice on the same Job ‚Äî typically when the Job
+controller restarts during a Pod's terminating window and
+re-creates a replacement before observing the original's
+exit. Two failure modes follow:
+
+- *Both Pods produce the same outcome.* Both write to the same
+  `work/<slug>-<variant_id>` ref via `git push`; the second
+  push is a no-op (`Already up to date` for an identical SHA).
+  Both emit `EDEN_OUTCOME` lines on stdout; the host reads
+  pod logs from whichever Pod the Job controller selected as
+  the "primary" (Job's pod-template-hash). Outcome: one
+  `VariantSubmission`; chapter 4 ¬ß4.2 idempotent-resubmit
+  applies even if both somehow ran the Phase 3 submit.
+- *Pods produce different outcomes.* (E.g., one OOM-killed
+  mid-push, the other completed.) The first Pod's `git push`
+  may leave a different ref-tip than the second Pod
+  attempts. The wrapper's `git push origin` per ¬ß3.6 will
+  refuse to overwrite (default `update-refs` rejects
+  non-fast-forward); the second Pod's wrapper writes
+  `outcome=error` to its own outcome.json. The host reads
+  one of the two `EDEN_OUTCOME` lines; whichever it sees, the
+  variant ends up in a coherent state because the host's
+  reachability check (¬ß3.4 step 6) re-runs against the
+  current Gitea ref. If the host's read picks the
+  failed-second-Pod's outcome, the variant terminalizes as
+  `error` even though a valid `commit_sha` was pushed ‚Äî
+  acceptable correctness loss; the next ideation cycle can
+  re-attempt.
+
+The host does NOT attempt to deduplicate Pods at the k8s
+level (it would have to query `pod-template-hash` and
+arbitrate, which is not idempotent itself). It relies on the
+existing chapter 4 ¬ß4.2 submission-equivalence rule plus
+chapter 3 ¬ß3.3 reachability to keep the store-side state
+coherent under duplicate-Pod execution. Documented in the
+new reference-binding chapter under "Duplicate Pod handling".
 
